{
  "texts": [
    "35 In particular, under the inversion transformation z → -1 z,∂Φ(z) → 1 z 2 ∂Φ - 1 z - 1 z, such that (∂Φ) † 0 = -(∂Φ) 0 -1.This anomalous transformation law is precisely why we found additional poles away from insertion points in ∂φ(z), which came with a residue of 1.",
    "These poles should be interpreted as the location of background charges for Φ (or equivalently for iκ 2) which are spurious singularities.",
    "From the boundary perspective, these charges should sit at x = ∞, which are the poles of the covering map.",
    "Recall that our choice of chart in section 2.3 covered the region where ξ + ̸ = 0 and so the point x = ∞ corresponds to these omitted points via the incidence relation x = γ = -ξ - ξ +.",
    "This means we have precisely N Γ charges sitting at {z * a } (the preimages of x = ∞) as argued earlier.To better understand what is going on, we consider the behaviour of a correlation function of ground states (3.8) under this transformation generated by K. After the integral over moduli space, correlation functions depend on the following data: the location {x i } on the boundary where the vertex operators are inserted and the ramification {w i } at that insertion."
